{"title_page": "The Mikey Show", "text_new": "{{Infobox radio show\n| name          = The Mokey Show\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| other_names   = \n| format        = [[Alternative music]] afternoon drive program\n| runtime       = \n| start_time    = \n| end_time      = \n| runtime_note  = \n| country       = \n| language      = [[California English|English]]\n| home_station  = [[KFBG (FM)|KFMB-FM]]\n| syndicates    = local show only\n| television    = \n| presenter     = Mikey Esparza\n| starring      = \n| announcer     = \n| creator       = \n| writer        = \n| director      = \n| senior_editor = \n| editor        = \n| producer      = \n| exec_producer = \n| narrated      = \n| rec_location  = The KFMB Station Studios.\n| rem_location  = \n| oth_location  = \n| first_aired   = 2017\n| last_aired    = \n| num_series    = \n| num_episodes  = \n| audio_format  = FM Stereo\n| opentheme     = \n| othertheme    = \n| endtheme      = \n| sponsor       = \n| website       =  {{URL|mikeyshow.com}} \n| podcast       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''''The Mikey Show''''' is an afternoon drive program currently airing in [[San Diego, California|San Diego]]. It recently was on hiatus from 2012 to 2017.\n\nPrior to its reboot, it was a controversial shock jock morning drive program syndicated across the Southwest.\n\n==History==\nThe Mikey Show earned its name from show host Mikey Esparza. He worked in radio his entire adult life all over the country, from Rochester, New York; to Dallas, Texas.\n\nThe Mikey Show was once syndicated, having aired on [[KSJO]] in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]] and [[KEGL]] in [[Dallas, Texas]] but was let go from both stations after creating a controversial parody song.{{cn|date=February 2015}} Esparza did the evening slot on [[KIOZ]] from 7:00 p.m. to 12:00 am from the late 1990s until 2004, broadcasting to both San Jose and Dallas via satellite.{{cn|date=February 2015}} His stint in the evening slot ended a week after he started broadcasting the morning drive in early 2004 and was fired for a stint he did about kidnapping victim [[Erica Pratt]].{{cn|date=February 2015}}  His return to San Diego came on the heels of [[Howard Stern]]\u2019s departure for satellite radio{{cn|date=February 2015}} where he quickly established a loyal fan base known as the \u201cM1s\u201d{{cn|date=February 2015}} and became the highest rated morning show in San Diego.{{cn|date=February 2015}} The show aired on [[KIOZ]] until late December 2009 when it  was announced that Esparza would not be given a chance to renew his contract.{{cn|date=February 2015}} His former cast remained at [[KIOZ]] to and continued their own show now entitled ''[[The Show (radio program)|The Show]]'' on January 4, 2010.\n\nOn January 12, 2010, it was announced on mikeyshow.com that The Mikey Show moved to 94.9.<ref>Announcement written by Mikey http://www.mikeyshow.com/main/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=56:announcement&catid=35:mikeyshow-blog&Itemid=1</ref> The Mikey Show debuted live on February 1, 2010.\n\nOn March 07, 2012 it was announced that The Mikey Show was no longer on 94.9. FM 94/9\u2019s senior V.P. and general manager Rick Jackson announced March 07 at 8:00 a.m. via a taped statement that its morning-talk Mikey Show would no longer be a part of the station\u2019s morning drive-time lineup.<ref>{{cite web|last=Monk|first=Barnaby|title=FM 94/9 Cancels Morning Talk Mikey Show|url=http://www.sandiegoreader.com/weblogs/jam-session/2012/mar/08/fm-949-cancels-morning-talk-emmikey-showem/|publisher=San Diego Reader|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 09, 2016 Jay Isbell stated on his podcast that there were hurt feelings behind the scenes on the Mikey Show while it was on the air.  These feelings divide Lauren and Woods from working with Mikey at this time.   <ref>{{cite web|last=Isbell|first=Jay|title=The Jay Show 90 Mikey Reunion Show|url=https://soundcloud.com/jay-isbell/the-jay-show-90-mikey-reunion-show|publisher=SoundCloud|accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 2017 it was announced that The Mikey Show would be airing on the afternoon drive on San Diego's KFMB 100.7.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/167933/kfmb-100-7-kfm-bfm-san-diego-adds-the-mikey-show-f|title=100.7 KFM-BFM San Diego adds the Mikey Show for Afternoons}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, it was announced that Mikey and KFMB were parting ways.  It was later noted that Mikey's contract was not renewed by the station.\n\nOn August 5, 2019 Mikey announced that he was moving to Tucson, AZ and would be doing the drive-time broadcast for a new radio station, The Drive 101.7.\n\n==Controversy==\n''The Mikey Show'' was criticized for its potential to harm children, some going as far as charging that it engages in the \"sexual exploitation of children to gain an audience.\"<ref name=Concerned>{{cite web\n  | last =Kleder\n  | first =Martha\n  | title =Fighting Back: Moms Battle Clear Channel\u2019s Shock Jock \u2018Mikey\u2019\n  | work =\n  | publisher =Concerned Women for America\n  | date= May 14, 2003\n  | url =http://www.cwfa.org/printerfriendly.asp?id=3956&department=&categoryid=\n  | format =Text\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate = 2007-01-23}}\n</ref> ''The Mikey Show'' set off a storm of criticism when, in 2004,  Esparza jokingly gave kidnapping tips to listeners following the kidnapping and subsequent escape of 7-year-old [[Erica Pratt]].<ref name=Concerned/><ref>{{cite news|last =Zahn|first=Paula|title=Abducted Philadelphia Girl Escapes Captors|work =CNN.com/Transcripts|publisher=CNN|date= July 24, 2002|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0207/24/ltm.12.html|accessdate = 2007-01-23}}</ref> The station subsequently fired Esparza for the gag.<ref name=AmericanFamily>{{cite web|authors=Rusty Pugh and Jody Brown|title=Bay Area Rids Itself of Profane Shock Jock|work=American Family Association|publisher=|date=September 23, 2002|url=http://headlines.agapepress.org/archive/9/afa/232002a.asp|format =|doi=|accessdate = 2007-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Fost|first=Dan|title=Clear Channel radio owners force shock jocks to eat their words|work=San Francisco Chronicle|pages=|publisher=|date=October 3, 2002|url =http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2002/10/03/BU36345.DTL|accessdate = 2007-01-23}}</ref> Esparza has also been criticed for simulating [[marijuana]] smoking on the air<ref>{{cite news|last=Garvin|first=Glen|title=Clearing the air: Has raunchy radio crossed the line?|work=The Miami Herald|pages=|publisher=|date=October 10, 2004|url=http://www.parentstv.org/PTC/news/2004/stern_miamiherald.htm|accessdate = 2007-01-23 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061210230620/http://www.parentstv.org/PTC/news/2004/stern_miamiherald.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-12-10}}\n</ref> and producing a parody song about artist R. Kelly's legal troubles, specifically being accused of [[statutory rape]].<ref name=AmericanFamily/>\n\nAfter arriving in San Diego the show became more mellow due to Esparza's embrace of [[Christianity]], with a billboard campaign advertising his contrasts labeling him both an addict and a [[Christians|Christian]]. Esparza often spoke of his love for [[Jesus]] and spoke openly about his past problems with [[substance abuse]].<ref name=Agent>{{cite news|last=Leighton|first=Ken|title=Get a Better Agent, Mikey|work=San Diego Reader|pages=|publisher=|date=July 27, 2006|url=http://www.sandiegoreader.com/news/2006/jul/27/get-better-agent-mikey/|accessdate=2007-01-23}} (Second story down on page)</ref>\n\n==KBZT Cast Members==\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2015}}\nThe new show on [http://www.fm949sd.com FM94/9] San Diego's [[KBZT]] had a cast of four: Mike Esparza (Host), Steven Woods (Sports), Jay Isbell (Producer), and Lauren O'Brien (Assistant Producer).\n\nMikey was in radio for over 20 years. In December 2009 after a very controversial breakup of his former show, Mike was left to build a whole new team on his own.\n\nSteven Woods and Mikey crossed paths when Mikey was in Dallas on the Eagle. Woods and Baumann were two characters often on KIOZ's Mikey Show that Eddie and Mikey did the voices for.{{clarify|reason=Who is Baumann?|date=February 2015}} Baumann was an older gentleman always trying to teach \"The Kid\" (Woods) some class about high priced suits, expensive cars and proper etiquette.\n\nJay is a former employee of [[Clear Channel Communications|Clear Channel]] Communications. He was the promotions director until January 2009 when Clear Channel had a massive budget cut and laid off 9% of their staff, Jay was part of that 9%. From there Jay went on to create his own promotions company, named Isbell Production. He was hired to do the 28hr show 2009 for KIOZ's Mikey Show.\n\nLauren is a stand up comedian and was discovered by Mikey when he found her on YouTube. She offers a lot of character voices and has a dry, sarcastic sense of humor.\n\n==KIOZ Cast Members==\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2015}}\nWhen the Mikey Show aired on San Diego's [[KIOZ]] it had a cast of five: Mikey, \"Boston\" Rob, Eddie, Ashlee, and Sky. Up until early 2009 the show had a sixth cast member by the name of Sean, he was laid off by [[Clear Channel Communications|Clear Channel]] due to budget cuts.\n\nOn July 13, 2011 [[KBZT]] conducted mass layoffs which included Mikey Show News girl Sienna Feerrar. No immediate information was given as to the cause of the layoffs.\n\nProfessional American Football Player [[Jeff Garcia]] went to high school with Mike.{{cn|date=February 2015}} Jeff appeared (via telephone) on the show. Mikey attributed Jeff's success to Mikey's bench-warming, and Jeff in turn mentioned that Mikey was busy watching the girls. Jeff also acknowledged that Mikey was \"DJing back then, telling it like it is!\"\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links